<user_id>101227739129106542860</user_id><user_name>Matt Nelson</user_name><time>1543598724834<//time><Rate>1</Rate>< Text>
Watch out for this station if you're using fuel rewards.  They rip you off by only giving you 5c per gallon even when you have 30c.  This has been going on since the new owner took over.  First they tell you that you did something wrong, and then when you prove that you did enter your ID (because they did give you 5c off for that) then they admit that their system isn't working.  If you complain they won't do anything for you.  I also called FR and they won't do anything either and they say it's the station's problem.  I think this is a scam.  Most shell stations the pump will ask you if you'd like to use your rewards or not, but at this one they flash the 5c by in about 1/10 of a second and then just apply the 5c.  If you're not paying attention to the price you will go ahead and pump your gas and after you fill the tank it's too late.  If you're using the Tmobile Tuesday 25c it will expire on Friday.  With my tank now full I guess I'm SOL on using that now.  The new owners may end up going down in a class action lawsuit.  I'm seriously considering contacting a lawyer.  I don't really like that (because the lawyers usually get most of the money), but this new owner needs to know that they can't keep ripping people off.< /Text>

<time>1622341874142< /time><Text>The good thing first: The sale person, Harry, was very friendly and not pushy at all. I never felt pressured at all during my visit.

Regarding the rest of my experience:
Went there to take a look at 2 preowned cars, a 2016 Kia Sorento and a 2018 Hyundai Tucson. I called a week ahead to make sure that both are available. A day before the reached out to me and assured me that both cars would be ready.

When I showed up in the morning they told me that the Kia was actually not available because they had shipped it somewhere else a few days ago. First red flag.

I still wanted to take a look at the Hyundai. On the outside it looked fine. Inside however, it looked like that hadn't really bothered to clean the car. The backseats had weird spots and I don't know whether they actually had tried to get rid of them. There were a bunch of paint like smears that should have been removed prior. When I looked at the trunk there were still some shopping receipts the previous owner had lost there, plus it didn't look like they had properly vacuumed.

It seemed to have a mechanical issue but that is not something you can blame them for. I left without buying the car.</Text>< pictures>

<rate>5< /rate>< Text>
My wife and I were driving north from LA to Marin County to visit family when my Infiniti starting acting up on the I-5 near Coalinga.  The engine was hesitating so badly that I had to exit the highway and look on my smart phone for a nearby Infiniti dealer.  Of course there were none.  The closest dealer was in Merced, and I didn't trust a roadside repair service to identify, and fix, the problem.  I discovered there was a dealer in San Raphael, my destination point, and called there to find out if my car was safe to drive another 100+ miles doing what it was doing.  I spoke with David T. in the Service Dept of Infiniti of Marin.  After David listened to my description of the car's behavior, he said he thought it would be safe for me to drive to the dealership.  When I got to San Raphael I drove straight to the dealership and unloaded my car into my host's vehicle.  A couple of hours later, David called and said the mechanics had identified the problem ( two faulty spark plugs and a bad ignition coil).  After waiting a day for the coil to arrive, I got my car back and drove safely home.  David T. called me several times to keep my updated on the progress of the repairs, and I got back a freshly-washed vehicle to travel home in.  The dealership has a comfortable waiting area and a GREAT coffee machine.  Infiniti of Marin is a quality place to deal with.  Highly recommend.</Text>

He added an extra $1500 to my loan amount without Explaining why it was even on there and simply asked "how does this look? I am on my 3rd Infiniti and one of the reasons I keep buying them- in addition to the fact it is a great car- is the service department at Infiniti Marin.  I have found them to be very reliable and trustworthy.  They never recommend repairs unless they are necessary.  For example, I have over 74k miles on my 2007 M35, and have still not have to had the brakes redone.  Every time I go in for an oil change, I inquire about whether the brakes should be relined, and I have always been told that they are still good, they'll recheck next time.  Their prices are very competitive, and I wouldn't think of taking my car anywhere else.</Text>

< text>

Infiniti of Marin took the proper steps to investigate the issue and ended up replacing the engine as the vehicle was still covered under warranty. <Text>Never would purchase another Infiniti again nor would recommend anyone to buy one. Not because the brand isnt good or anything but just for the fact that Infiniti would not engage with you if the car is out of warranty and you run into some serious reliability problems.

This is not a bad reflection on Marin Infiniti itself; the service manager who attended to my car was very helpful and she was really sympathetic to my issues. However, the way Infiniti distanced itself from the issue saying it is a older car speaks volume about their customer engagement.

Wear and tear on moving parts are pretty normal on a old car. This is normal. However, I had issues with overheating, TWICE, and both times I was left stranded. Paid a huge amount of money of course but this is not due to usage. This is some inherent issue with the car itself I believe but Infiniti wouldnt even look into it. They are more than happy to keep servicing the car which is a money pit for them anyways. First time, they said something blocked the radiator causing it to blow out and next time, the fans on the radiator was intermittently not working. I dont know how usage can cause issues like this.

<Text>This place is open and has screens and masks as a requirement as measures against covid. You can dine-in or outside on the patio, and the service is very fast. < text>
Surprisingly great food for such a hidden location.  Not the ideal place for a restaurant but these small gems are worth finding.

I don't get the pho here as their specialties are better.  The clay pot combo is a must order as well as the phnom Penh were delicious.  A great spot to visit during San Diego rains and colder weather.

<Gmap_id>0x80dc007222e4326d:0x7d28e0448cad183a< /Gmap_id><Pics>None<//Pics><name>Christina Gaunce< /name>< text>
This place is heaven! Their Tofu lemongrass Bahn Mi and Tofu Papaya salad are devine! Imagine a lemongrass pesto of sorts on a soft and crispy french bread. So Good!

And yes, the tofu versions are even super delicious even to those who don't like tofu/prefer meat. This is a must visit place for vegetarians and non-vegetarians.

I must say that I was not impressed with the vegetarian pho (it was a little bland to me) but I have non-veg friends who think the chicken pho is phenominal.

There prices have increased in the last few years, which makes it even more of a rare occasion/treat!<//text>

<Rate>4<//Rate><user_id>109028906014708659267<//user_id><Pics>None</Pics>< review>
Came here and tried their P1 pho noodle soup (rare steak, brisket, flank steak, tendon and tripe) and shrimp spring rolls.

P1 pho noodle soup:
Portion size was perfect. Enjoyed the various pieces of meat. Weren't over cooked. Broth was good. Could be a little stronger with more in depth flavor. Did seem a little diluted. For the most part, the noodles are slightly separated for you, as opposed to the "brick" noodles that most places do. We all know it's pre packaged but still. The side vegetables were fresh.

The shrimp rolls were excellent. Reminded me of it being homemade.  They had the right proportions of each ingredient and the peanut sauce was excellent. The dish comes with 2 rolls cut into a total of 4 pieces.

Service was great. Very attentive to water level. It is a small place so seating is somewhat limited. You can easily fit a group of 4 people. I would say service can be slow at times if they are busy because you just don't need that many people to work the front of the house. Parking is a non issue. They accept cc (including amex).

I would definitely come back here.<//review>

P1 pho noodle soup:
Portion size was perfect. Enjoyed the various pieces of meat. Weren't over cooked. Broth was good. Could be a little stronger with more in depth flavor. Did seem a little diluted. I have had it before and you can not go wrong with this one. A must try. They have a huge menu to choose from you will find something. Love their spring rolls too with the peanut sauce.</text>< Pics>

0x80dbffebd0652497:0x5add788bca9aa699<//gmap_id>
<text>They do not have the beloved Costco alcohol selection sadly. I get it, it's a business center focused more on restaurant and office supplies but it is California and many offices offer drinks for lunch or after work. It seemed to be less hectic and had better vibes than regular Costcos. Bottom line, I would still good here in the future for all of my household grocery shopping in the future.

Other than that it has some really cool items and bigger bulk selections of meat and produce you won't find at other regular Costco centers. Looked like they had some really good commercial cooking appliances. They also have heaters in stock which is a big commodity currently with all of the outdoor dining. The non alcoholic drink selection seemed to be a lot better than other Costcos as well.

The staff seemed to be a lot friendlier and more helpful than at the other Costcos as well. The door greater was happy to be there, people stocking were cheerful and happy, and the cashier made the process fun for everyone. I wish every Costco trip could be like this. Perhaps the customers are a bit easier to deal here, I don't know but whatever it is, it is working for them.<//text>< Name>
Jesse Watson</Name>

1572295105459</date>
<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
Business Center Costco is not for everyone. You'll find that this location is geared toward restaurants and mini-mart type operations. Don't think for a second that you can do your monthly household shopping here. I'm always surprised by how many patrons come in expecting to find all their regular Costco items here. If you want to find a wide variety of snack foods in single-serving bags, candy, gum, mints, or a huge variety of soft drinks, this is your place. If you're looking for items to stock your large office with basic office supplies, frozen and non-perishable foods, coffee and tea, this is your place. Need to supply your deli? Need a dozen #10 cans of tomato sauce? Need four kinds of sweetener packets? Perfect place. They DO have a walk-up food concession here so you can still get that low-cost lunch item and a fountain drink here. Prices are the same as the retail membership sites.<//text>

<name>Ronald Moore< /name>< Date>
1548289971573</Date>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
It's a Costco but has products more oriented toward businesses rather than home. This means big, big boxes of stuff. I'm talking whole sheep carcasses, 100 pound bags of potatoes and so on. They also sell commercial appliances and cookware like you would find at a kitchen supply store. They do carry "home sized" items and things different from the warehouse stores. There is not a large overlap between the two types of store. The business store is well worth a visit and the one I go to is clean and well run. Personnel are friendly, lines are short and there is plenty of room to push your cart.< /text>

< date>
1527701561689< /date>
<GmapID>0x80dbffebd0652497:0x5add788bca9aa699<//GmapID><Pics>None<//Pics><resp>None<//resp>< user>
116233538932653603204< /user>
< review>
I occasionally visit the Costco Business center because they have some different items than my normal Costco center. I don't own a business, just shop for my family here. Some items I get here include individually packaged snacks for the kids (they have many more options of potato chips, bars, pretzels, popcorn,etc than the normal Costco), coffee flavorings by Torani, and drinks (they sell 48 LaCroix packages that are all one flavor vs regular Costco sells a mixed pack with the lime flavor in it that none of my family likes). They also sell different Frozen and refrigerated items that may be of interest to other families like mine, for example Lunchables, tater tots, soft pretzels.
Things you should be aware of, it's even more no-frill than the regular Costco. They have tons of items that might be of interest if you worked in a commercial kitchen or owned a convenience store (candy, beverages, take-out containers, large cuts of meat, huge quantities of certain produce).
*They do not sell any alcohol at this location, fyi.< /review>
<name>Emily Rockwell< /name></record>
